<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=111214861&t=artid%3dc85de45a-c898-48a2-aab7-9d5e2b0adb30%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=111214861&t=artid%3dc85de45a-c898-48a2-aab7-9d5e2b0adb30%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>In Motherwell, Eastern Cape, four armed robbers have targeted stokvels since the beginning of December.On 3 December, three armed suspects kicked open the door of a church on Mhenga Street where stokvel members were busy counting their money. The thugs took the cash as well as six cellphones.The same day, four armed men entered a house in Wells Estate, Nelson Mandela Bay, and fled the scene with the stokvel money.On 4 December, three armed thugs invaded an Ikamvelihle house and stole the savings.In Kwazakele, Eastern Cape on 5 December, three armed men forced a parked car’s doors open and shot the 52-year-old driver in his leg. One of the two elderly women passengers ran into a house and hid in the toilet but the thugs kicked the door down and took the cash.A 45-women stokvel was also robbed as they gathered at a house in Ga-Seaphole, Limpopo this month.Yesterday, in Modjadjiskloof outside Tzaneen, a 42-year-old woman was robbed of stokvel money.Limpopo police spokesman Lieutenant-Colonel Moatshe Ngoepe said it is safer for payments to be electronically transferred into each member’s personal account or to a debit card.
